===Radio, stage and film===
Gatiss appears frequently in [[:en:BBC_Radio|BBC Radio]] productions, including the science fiction comedy ''[[:en:Nebulous|Nebulous]]'' and ''[[:en:The_Further_Adventures_of_Sherlock_Holmes|The Further Adventures of Sherlock Holmes]]'' story ''[[:en:The_Shameful_Betrayal_of_Miss_Emily_Smith|The Shameful Betrayal of Miss Emily Smith]]''. In 2009 he was [[:en:The_Man_in_Black|The Man in Black]] when BBC Radio 7 revived the character (originally played by [[:en:Valentine_Dyall|Valentine Dyall]] and [[:en:Edward_de_Souza|Edward de Souza]]) to introduce a series of five creepy audio dramas. He is also involved with theatre, having penned the play ''The Teen People'' in the early 1990s, and appeared in a successful run of the play ''[[:en:'Art'_(play)|'Art']]'' in 2003 at the Whitehall Theatre in London. In film, he has starred in ''[[:en:Sex_Lives_of_the_Potato_Men|Sex Lives of the Potato Men]]'' (2004) and had minor roles in ''[[:en:Birthday_Girl|Birthday Girl]]'' (2001), ''[[:en:Bright_Young_Things|Bright Young Things]]'' (2003), ''[[赛末点|赛末点]]'' (2005) and ''[[:en:Starter_for_10_(film)|Starter for 10]]'' (2006). ''[[:en:The_League_of_Gentlemen's_Apocalypse|The League of Gentlemen's Apocalypse]]'', a film based on the television series, co-written by and starring Gatiss, was released in June 2005. He also plays the recurring character of [[:en:The_Passenger_(Sapphire_and_Steel)|Gold]] in the audio revival of ''[[:en:Sapphire_and_Steel|Sapphire and Steel]]'' produced by [[:en:Big_Finish_Productions|Big Finish Productions]]. Gatiss also appeared in [[:en:Edgar_Wright|Edgar Wright]]'s fake trailer for [[:en:Grindhouse_(film)|Grindhouse]], [[:en:Grindhouse_(film)#Don't|Don't]], a homage to 70's Hammer Horrors.

In the 2008 English language  re-release of the cult 2006 Norwegian animated film ''[[:en:Free_Jimmy|Free Jimmy]]'', Gatiss voiced the character of "Jakki", a heavy-set, bizarrely dressed biker member of the "Lappish Mafia". In this his voice is used along with the other actors of ''League of Gentlemen'' such as Steve Pemberton and Reece Shearsmith. The dialogue was written by [[:en:Simon_Pegg|Simon Pegg]] and other actors included Pegg himself, [[:en:Woody_Harrelson|Woody Harrelson]], and [[大衛·田納特|大衛·田納特]], who worked with Gatiss on 《神秘博士》.

Mark appeared in the stage adaptation of [[佩德罗·阿尔莫多瓦尔|佩德罗·阿尔莫多瓦尔]]'s ''[[关于我母亲的一切|关于我母亲的一切]]'' at the [[:en:Old_Vic|Old Vic]] in London from 25 Aug-24 Nov 2007. He won much critical acclaim for his portrayal of the semi-transsexual Agrado.

Mark was scheduled to perform in ''Darker Shores'' by Michael Punter, a ghost story for all the family, at [[:en:Hampstead_Theatre|Hampstead Theatre]] 3 December 2009 - 16 January 2010 but had to withdraw after a serious family illness. [[:en:Tom_Goodman-Hill|Tom Goodman-Hill]] took over his role.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.watfordobserver.co.uk/leisure/theatre/cfutheatrefeatures/4787207.It___s_on_with_the_show/ |title=It's on with the show (From Watford Observer) |publisher=Watfordobserver.co.uk |date=2009-12-10 |accessdate=2010-10-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502183237/http://www.watfordobserver.co.uk/leisure/theatre/cfutheatrefeatures/4787207.It___s_on_with_the_show/ |archive-date=2014-05-02 |dead-url=yes }}</ref>

