==写作==
Fulfilling a lifelong dream, Gatiss has written four episodes for the 2005-revived BBC television series 《神秘博士》. His first, "[[:en:The_Unquiet_Dead|The Unquiet Dead]]" was only the third episode of the revived series in 2005; the second, "[[:en:The_Idiot's_Lantern|The Idiot's Lantern]]", aired the following year in the second series.<ref>{{cite web |title= Mark Gatiss Presents Doctor Who Documentary |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/s4/features/bulletins/bulletin_090623_01 | publisher = BBC }}</ref> After a sabbatical from the third series (in which he acted rather than wrote for), and his submitted script for the fourth series, involving Nazis and the British Museum, remaining unmade, he eventually returned to the programme in 2010, writing "[[:en:Victory_of_the_Daleks|Victory of the Daleks]]" for the fifth series, and "[[:en:Night_Terrors_(Doctor_Who)|Night Terrors]]" for the sixth.

Gatiss has written two episodes of 《[[神探夏洛克|神探夏洛克]]》, a modern [[歇洛克·福尔摩斯|歇洛克·福尔摩斯]] series co-produced by himself and [[史蒂芬·莫法特|史蒂芬·莫法特]]. The unaired pilot was shot in January 2009 and a full series was commissioned, eventually airing a three-episode series in August 2010 (including Gatiss's episode "[[:en:The_Great_Game_(Sherlock)|The Great Game]]"). A second series (featuring Gatiss's second contribution "[[:en:The_Hounds_of_Baskerville|The Hounds of Baskerville]]") aired in January 2012.

Gatiss wrote and performed the comedy sketches ''The Web of Caves'', ''The Kidnappers'' and ''The Pitch of Fear'' for the BBC's "[[:en:Doctor_Who_spoofs|''Doctor Who'' Night]]" in 1999 with 《小不列颠》的 [[:en:David_Walliams|David Walliams]], and played [[:en:Master_(Doctor_Who)|the Master]] in the ''Doctor Who Unbound'' play ''[[:en:Sympathy_for_the_Devil_(Doctor_Who_audio)|Sympathy for the Devil]]'' under the name "Sam Kisgart", a pseudonym he later used for a column in ''[[:en:Doctor_Who_Magazine|Doctor Who Magazine]]''. (The pseudonym is an anagram]of "Mark Gatiss", a nod to [[:en:Anthony_Ainley|Anthony Ainley]], who was sometimes credited under an anagram to conceal the Master's identity from the viewers.) The pseudonym was used again in television listings magazines when he appeared in episode four of ''Psychoville'', so as not to spoil his surprise appearance in advance{{citation needed|date=October 2011}}.

In mainstream print, Gatiss is responsible for a biography of the film director [[詹姆斯·惠尔|詹姆斯·惠尔]]. His first non-《神秘博士》 novel, ''[[:en:The_Vesuvius_Club|The Vesuvius Club]]'', was published in 2004, for which he was nominated in the category of Best Newcomer in the 2006 [[:en:British_Book_Awards|British Book Awards]]. A follow up, ''[[:en:The_Devil_in_Amber|The Devil in Amber]]'', was released on 6 November 2006. It transports the main character, [[:en:Lucifer_Box|Lucifer Box]], from the [[:en:Edwardian_era|Edwardian era]] in the first book to the roaring Twenties/Thirties. A third and final Lucifer Box novel, ''[[:en:Black_Butterfly_(novel)|Black Butterfly]]'', was published on 3 November 2008 by [[:en:Simon_&_Schuster|Simon & Schuster]]<ref name=simonandschuster>{{cite web|url=http://authors.simonandschuster.com/Mark-Gatiss/28437914 |title=Mark Gatiss - Official Publisher Page|publisher=[[:en:Simon_&_Schuster|Simon & Schuster]] }}</ref>.

Gatiss also wrote, co-produced and appeared in ''[[:en:Crooked_House_(TV_series)|Crooked House]]'', a ghost story that was broadcast on [[英國廣播公司第四台|英國廣播公司第四台]] during Christmas 2008.
